//alone * Volunteer your time with a local charity * If you are religious, attend a religious service or group meeting * Call or text a friend you haven\'t heard from in a while To start to connect with others, consider one of the following: If you are feeling lonely or on your own, it\'s very important for you to try to reach out to others and try to find others who can connect with and spend time with. First it is important to recognize that living through a traumatic experience can often lead to avoiding other people-whether it\'s because you\'re uncertain or fearful about how you\'ll act around them ,or you just want to be alone. Everyone feels this way sometimes, and it\'s especially common for those who have traumatic experiences.It can sometimes be hard to relate to others,or to feel understood by them. You might even feel annoyed or irritable when you\'re around others Feeling alone or isolated is a common experience.
//trust Having someone you can trust and open up to is a gift. It does not mean that person has to be perfect just that you feel comfortable enough to let them in on your experience of the world and know that it\'s okay to be yourself. Take a moment to appreciate having someone you can trust.Research has shown that the act of expressing appreciation or gratitude to another person can really help lift your own spirits. Is there someone in your life that you can call or text out of the blue? Just engaging in a conversation with someone you can trust can often be very helpful.Make a short call or visit to a friend or loved one, and if you\'re feeling adventurous,open up to them a bit more than you usually do.
//quiz5 Problems related to PTSD Some other problems are more common for people with PTSD.These include: * depression * panic attacks * alcohol and substance use problems * increased risk of medical problems
//quiz4 PTSD symptoms usually appear soon after a traumatic experience ,however,in some cases symptoms do not appear for months or even years after the trauma.For some people who experience symptoms early, these symptoms go away on their own.For others,these symptoms can last for many years, especially if they do not seek help. How long PTSD lasts also depends on whether effective treatment is received.
//quiz3 After trauma,it iss normal to be in shock,have painful memories,and be upset by reminders.Trauma can also change how people think about themselves,others,and the world to more extreme ideas like \'nowhere is safe\' or \'no one can be trusted.\' For most,these reactions will lessen over time.But for some, these reactions continue and can be severe enough to disturbed everyday life.
//quiz2 No matter how long you have lived with PTSD, there are treatments that can help.
//quiz1 Post traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) is caused by witnessing,experiencing,or learning about someone close to you who experienced traumatic events (such as actual or threatened death,serious injury, or sexual violence). The good news is that PTSD is treatable PTSD includes 4 types of symptoms: 1. Re-experiencing or reliving the trauma, such as: * Disturbing memories or nightmares * Feeling or acting like the trauma is happening again (flashbacks) * Becoming very upset when reminded of the trauma 2. Persistent avoidance such as : * Avoiding memories about the trauma * Avoiding thoughts or memories closely associated with traumatic events. 3. Negative thoughts and moods * Self blame for trauma * Felling detached or isolating from other. * Trouble feeling positive emotions like happiness and love. 4.More on-edge and reactive,such as: * Feeling on guard * Startling easily * Problem concentrating
//quiz6 If you think you have PTSD, talk with your doctor or schedule an evaluation with a mental health professional. Also, remember that some people may develop other problems like depression or substance use after a trauma If your trauma was less than a month or two ago and you are not in too much distress or having problems function in everyday life,then you may want to see if your symptoms get better on their own. If you still don`t feel well after one or two months,seek professional help
//quiz7 *Relax *Identify *Decide First,do something to help yourself relax (such as take some deep breaths,get a drink of water,or remind yourself that you can handle it." Second,identify what the trigger is then identify how now its different than then. Third,decide what to do.
//embarrassed Some people feel ashamed to need help or ask for help. But think about this: We are not alone in this world.People are here to help you now. Did you know that people who accept help after a stressful time do better than those who don/t get support? Seeking counselling does not mean you are non-functional If you dont feel better and it has been months or years,talking to a counselor may help so that problems do not become chronic or more severe
//about PTSD Coaching app is a mobile application for people with PostTraumatic Stress Disorder(PTSD) and those interested in learning more about it. This application provides : * Education about PTSD. * A direct connection to crisis support. * Information about professional treatment. * Tools for managing distress associated with Post traumatic Stress. //alone * Join a meetup group around a hobby or interest of yours * Write a letter or send an email to someone you care about * Try to do something nice to someone
//need It\'s normal for people who have experienced trauma to have some challenges adjusting afterwards.Sometimes these challenges are severe, or last more than a few months. Whether you need help can only be determined by you and a trained healthcare professional. Remember, you don\'t have to wait for an emergency to speak to someone. The following problems are common after a trauma and can signal a need for more support: * Depression-feeling sad,down,or blue most of the time * Startling easily in response to loud or unexpected noises * Easily angered, aggressive/violet behavior * Reckless or aggressive driving * Having thoughts about suicide , or of hurting or killing someone else * Isolating oneself,withdrawal from friends and family
//grow Having healthy, satisfying support from other people in your life is important to having a good quality of life. If you\'ve already got at least some support, you\'re doing well. Having satisfying relationships with others requires some effort-showing those you care about that you have time for them and are interested in them. Taking the time to invest in your existing relationships can pay dividends- you\'ll probably feel better, and you\'ll strengthen your connections with people you already care about To grow your existing support,try one of the following: * Call a friend and invite them to do something with you this week * Take the time to do something with a friend or family member that you know they enjoy,even if you don/t enjoy. * Ask a family member to spend some quality time with you doing something that you both enjoy.
//seek Some trauma survivors seek counselling because they : * Have trouble with work and relationships * Avoid reminders but find memories around every corner * Feel very nervous or angry * Have trouble sleeping While these symptoms are common in the first month or two after a trauma,if you don/t feel better soon,then you should think about talking to a counselor. Also, some people find that: * Loved ones mean well but can/t help the way they need them to * Loved ones are far away and unavailable * The things they want to talk about feel too sensitive or private In these circumstances, talking to an expert can really help.
//who There are many experts who can help you if you seek care. You can read more here about the roles and duties of primary care physicians, social workers,psychologists,psychiatrists, and pastoral counselors/chaplains.
//embarrassed Some people feel ashamed to need help or ask for help.But think about this: * We are not alone in this world,people are here to help you. * Did you know that people who accept help after a stressful time do better than those who don/t get support? * Seeking counselling does not mean you are non-functional. * Counselling is not for weak or broken people.It takes courage to ask for help * Talk to a counselor if you don/t feel better in months so that the problem does not become chronic
